label chapter8:

    # [Scene: Reed Beds / Vendor Stalls | Early Afternoon — After a Storm]

    scene bg ch8_6b08b4_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low, continuous thrum of pumps; the market's usual hum reduced to voices clipped with shock, a child crying in the distance, a gust rattling a loose tarp.]
    # [Smell: Diesel tang from a work skiff, the metallic wetness of exposed marsh peat, and the faint smoke of overturned cooking coals.]
    "You were at the council twelve hours ago, the charter folded under your hand. The ascendant piano of promise still rings in your bones. And now the boardwalk is a wound with edges that smell of salt and fear."
    "You crouch at the break where the engineered clamp once sat—an arc of dark metal, now curled and twisted into the water like a blunt question. Jun kneels beside you, fingers ghosting over mud, his tablet"
    "screen throwing up a scatter of numbers. He keeps glancing at you, as if to measure how much of this is technical and how much is moral."
    show jun_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jun_park "The tide pulse shouldn't have exceeded design loads. Not by— (he swallows) —not by this much. If the installation was rushed, the scour beneath the decking could have compromised lateral support. The clamp failed along the seam."
    "You taste salt and copper. The words 'rushed' and 'installation' thread together in your head until they become the same animal. You remember meetings with engineers, the investor's timeline compressed by a fiscal quarter, Lina's tight-lipped"
    "nod, your own small phrasing of compromise—the gentle way you convinced yourself 'phased' meant 'safer'."
    "You stand, palms pressed to damp rail, and let the market fold around you: Marta's face red with anger; a woman stacking ruined jars of smoked fish; a boy who keeps patting his mother's soaked blanket as if it were an animal wounded."
    show marta_quin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marta_quin "They promised the shore would hold. They promised the work wouldn't start until—until people could plan.' (Her voice is a knife wrapped in old cotton—sudden tenderness with the edge of history.) 'Aria, you were there. You said this was the way."
    "Your name lands like a stone. Around you, a dozen other voices pick up the echo, not unkindness at first but the brittle weight of accusation. You feel the gathering of eyes — council aides, vendors, the occasional investor in a water-streaked coat trying to appear unhurt."
    show eli_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "You okay? You look like someone who carries tides in their chest."
    "You should meet his gaze. You want to. But the market is a species of tribunal and the eyes around you are lit by something sharper than worry."
    hide jun_park
    show aria_solen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_solen "We're trying to stop more timber from collapsing. Jun thinks the clamp failure is symptomatic—installation stress, accelerated timeline."

    eli_navarro "So the schedule broke the shore,' he says, then his mouth tightens. 'Or someone bent the schedule. Which is worse?"
    "You want to tell him how you chose the compromise, the exact words you used in the council, how you believed Lena's mitigations were enough. But every detail of past choices now opens like a wound that lets critics in. You breathe peat air and choose the partial truth."

    aria_solen "It was an accepted risk. We accepted conditions to get the pilot moving. Now the pilot's bleeding."
    "Jun looks up, eyes rimmed with exhaustion."
    hide marta_quin
    show jun_park at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jun_park "There's also evidence of an engineered failure pattern. These clamps—' (he taps the corrupted metal) '—they show atypical shear points. I don't have a fingerprint for intent, Aria. I have a pattern and a timestamp that coincides with accelerated installation windows."
    "Caden Holt steps forward from the cluster of council aides, his suit still holding rain beads like a calculated shine. He is careful, measured; the rhetoric has always been his tide pool—calm on the surface while currents run beneath."
    hide eli_navarro
    show caden_holt at center:
        zoom 0.7

    caden_holt "What we have here is regrettable. Coastal engineering is iterative. We mobilized faster because the storm window was closing. We will mobilize emergency funds. Blaming process without perspective won't rebuild the market."
    "Marta's laugh is hard and sudden."
    hide aria_solen
    show marta_quin at left:
        zoom 0.7

    marta_quin "Perspective? People lost stock and stalls, Caden. Kids lost their Saturday bread. Perspective doesn't buy seed or mend a child's shoes."
    "A vendor—barely older than you—shoves forward, his hand trembling."

    "Vendor" "You told us your plan would protect us. You were at the meetings. You stood beside the renderings and nodded like it was a promise."

    "The crowd's tenor shifts. Words become an undertow" "adviser', 'compromise', 'you accepted"
    "Your internal voice mills through possibilities and consequences—justice, expediency, political damage, the fragile thread of trust you braided with so many hands. Each possibility has teeth. You hear, under the market sound, the distant drone of"
    "a television news van wheeling into place. The council pavilion becomes a staging ground for narratives."
    hide jun_park
    hide caden_holt
    hide marta_quin

    scene bg ch8_6b08b4_2 at full_bg
    "Eli approaches, and this time his voice comes from closer quarters."
    show eli_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "You don't have to carry all of it alone, Aria. I can rally the Helix crew for temporary pontoons, patch the worst of the scour. We can keep vendors afloat while you—' (he falters) '—figure out the council."
    "You see the way hope sits on him—practical, immediate, trawled up from making-do. His solution is hands-on, like a bandage. His eyes, amber dimmed under rain, are complex; unless you look for softness you might read"
    "the strain as blame. He is trying to hold something—your shoulders, perhaps, or the larger project."
    show aria_solen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    aria_solen "I appreciate it. We need boots on the water. We also need answers."

    eli_navarro "Then let's get both. I'll pull men for pontoons. You—' (he searches your face) '—don't hide behind process when people are hurt."
    "That sentence lodges in your throat. His bluntness is not an accusation, strictly speaking, but it is a wedge. You feel the old reflex to protect the project, to triage optics first so the long work"
    "can continue. That reflex is what brought you to the council room and led you to accept a phased compromise. You wonder now whether 'phase' translated into 'hurry'."
    "Jun steps in, offering what he can—a place where data and consequence meet."
    show jun_park at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jun_park "We can sample the clamp residue. There may be metallurgy breakdown from improper torque or from deliberate sabotage. It will take hours. In the meantime, the council will convene. Lina said she'd call an emergency review."
    "At Lina's arrival, her face is pinched, eyes shining with a tired, diplomatic fatigue. She moves with the care of someone who has to be the bridge between rhetoric and restitution."
    hide eli_navarro
    show lina_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_voss "We will form an emergency committee. My office will request an independent structural audit. But we need calm testimony, documented claims—"
    "Marta, already short with council procedure, laughs bitterly."
    hide aria_solen
    show marta_quin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marta_quin "Calm testimony? People lost everything. Documented claims won't feed mouths this week."
    "The crowd begins to break into smaller knots—vendors huddling, council aides whispering. The coalition you helped build—the braided compromise that felt like a compromise-sizing of everything you loved—starts to fray along old fault lines: preservationists muttering against developers, investors flinching at the smell of legal exposure, aldermen retreating into process-speak."
    "Caden now chooses containment over empathy."
    hide jun_park
    show caden_holt at center:
        zoom 0.7

    caden_holt "Public outrage is predictable. We must secure the market, announce emergency aid, and emphasize our commitment to transparent investigation. Assign blame only when we have cause."

    "An ugly chorus answers" "Assign blame."
    "You stand in the center of these currents, feeling an old, private fear resurface—what if the compromise you brokered becomes the wedge that destroys the very community it aimed to save? You had wanted to weave trade-offs into resilience; now trade-offs read as betrayals."
    "Your chest tightens with inherited grief—the sibling lost to a storm is a memory that still arrives like a sudden tide. That grief is the ember beneath your decisions; it had propelled you into public life. Now that ember burns against you, and you smell smoke."
    "Eli presses a hand to your shoulder, solid and rough; you sense both his steadiness and impatience."
    hide lina_voss
    show eli_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "We can put planks across the worst of it. We can keep people trading, keep kids fed. But if we only paper over this so capital keeps rolling, people will remember how we chose speed over them."
    "Aria Solen: (after a long breath) 'I know.'"
    "Your voice sounds small. It is smaller than the chorus of accusation, smaller than the hiss of the pumps and the distant press. You want to write a statement, a defense; you want to summon words"
    "that will hold—'We did our best'—but you know honesty is its own heavy instrument. Your pragmatic streak warps into avoidance: you could quiet things now, fix optics, persuade investors not to pull out. Or you could"
    "lay yourself bare and ask for accountability. Or you could mobilize the market's memory—vendors and elders—to make the council listen in a way cold data never will."
    "Jun's tablet buzzes; new data scrolls up like a tide chart. He looks at you with an expression that is equal parts colleague and moralist—his scientific mind demanding you weigh evidence and consequence."
    hide marta_quin
    show jun_park at right:
        zoom 0.7

    jun_park "There will be finger-pointing, Aria. If you led negotiations that accepted those timeline concessions, you'll be in the line of sight. I can help with an independent analysis, but the political heat will crater reputations faster than the waves crater our shore."
    "You close your eyes for one steady beat and hear Rafi's voice—a braided line of memory, the old man walking the tideways and reciting names of channels like prayer. You think of responsibility not as a ledger but as a relationship you promised to tend."
    "A hush falls—the market's momentary quiet before fractured speech resumes. You are suddenly aware of the camera angle from a nearby livestream: someone in a council trench coat has pointed a microphone at you. The world"
    "wants a face to pin to this failure. The coalition's seams are visible now, and you can see the choices like doors that will change how people trust you, and whether the co-op you built survives."

    menu:
        "Rush to patch the damaged boardwalk with volunteers":
            "You bark orders, the Helix crew folds into a chain, and wet planks slide under hands. For an hour the market is a choreographed salvage; you feel useful, a stitch in the wound. But as evening comes the cameras still circle, hungry for names. The work soothes but does not absolve."
        "Stand in front of the crowd and speak without notes":
            "You climb the remaining upright of the boardwalk and let your voice carry—plain, small, honest. A few listeners hush, some scoff. The act of speaking publicly shifts the weather in the square: some eyes soften, others sharpen. You are no longer only a project manager; you are also a person who must answer."
        "Pull Jun aside and demand accelerated forensic analysis before going public":
            "You and Jun huddle under a tarpaulin while he plots data points and sampling sites. The focus calms you—facts are a language you trust. But while you chase evidence, the story in the press fills the silence with speculation, and the market's anger grows louder."

